  "why": "The paper provides a partial diagnostic insight by characterizing the properties of the discovered failures (referred to as 'inconsistencies'). The analysis correlates the failures with both the specific System Under Test (SUT) and the type of input mutation applied. For instance, the authors find that the two highest-performing SUTs on the benchmark dataset were paradoxically the ones that produced the highest number of inconsistencies. Furthermore, they analyze which mutation types were most effective, concluding that adding objects ('Add Car', 'Add Person') induced far more inconsistencies than merely changing an object's color. This analysis characterizes the failures by linking them to properties of the model (benchmark performance) and the structure of the input (mutation type), but it does not perform a deeper root-cause analysis to explain *why* these models fail by linking the failures to underlying vulnerabilities like training data bias, spurious features, or architectural weaknesses.",
